{
  "id": "algebra",
  "paper": 1,
  "title": "Algebra, Equations & Inequalities",
  "blurb": "Quadratic equations and inequalities, simultaneous equations, exponents and surds, and the nature of roots.",
  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "algebra-01",
      "difficulty": 1,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-factor",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x^2-7x+10=0$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$(x-2)(x-5)=0$",
            "$x=2$ or $x=5$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=2$ or $x=5$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$, correct to TWO decimal places: $3x^2+2x-4=0$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$x=\\dfrac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$ with $a=3$, $b=2$, $c=-4$",
            "$x=\\dfrac{-2\\pm\\sqrt{(2)^2-4(3)(-4)}}{2(3)}=\\dfrac{-2\\pm\\sqrt{52}}{6}$",
            "$x=0{,}87$ or $x=-1{,}54$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=0{,}87$ or $x=-1{,}54$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x(x-5)<6$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$x^2-5x-6<0$",
            "$(x-6)(x+1)<0$",
            "Critical values $x=-1$ and $x=6$; the parabola is below zero between the roots",
            "$-1<x<6$"
          ],
          "answer": "$-1<x<6$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-02",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-simultaneous",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve simultaneously for $x$ and $y$: $y=x+1$ and $x^2+y^2=25$.",
          "marks": 6,
          "solution": [
            "Substitute $y=x+1$ into $x^2+y^2=25$: $x^2+(x+1)^2=25$",
            "$x^2+x^2+2x+1=25$",
            "$2x^2+2x-24=0$, so $x^2+x-12=0$",
            "$(x+4)(x-3)=0$",
            "$x=-4$ or $x=3$",
            "If $x=-4$ then $y=-3$; if $x=3$ then $y=4$"
          ],
          "answer": "$(x;y)=(-4;-3)$ or $(x;y)=(3;4)$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-03",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-exp-equation",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $3^{x+1}+3^x=36$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$3^x(3+1)=36$",
            "$3^x=9=3^2$",
            "$x=2$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=2$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $\\sqrt{x+5}=x-1$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "Square both sides: $x+5=(x-1)^2=x^2-2x+1$",
            "$x^2-3x-4=0$",
            "$(x-4)(x+1)=0$, so $x=4$ or $x=-1$",
            "Check $x=-1$: LHS $=\\sqrt{4}=2$ but RHS $=-2$, so $x=-1$ is not valid",
            "$x=4$ only"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=4$ (the solution $x=-1$ is extraneous)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-04",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-formula",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$ by completing the square: $x^2+6x-2=0$. Leave your answer in simplest surd form.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$x^2+6x=2$",
            "$x^2+6x+9=2+9$",
            "$(x+3)^2=11$",
            "$x+3=\\pm\\sqrt{11}$",
            "$x=-3\\pm\\sqrt{11}$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=-3+\\sqrt{11}$ or $x=-3-\\sqrt{11}$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Hence write down the minimum value of $f(x)=x^2+6x-2$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "solution": [
            "From the completed square, $f(x)=(x+3)^2-11$",
            "Minimum value is $-11$ (at $x=-3$)"
          ],
          "answer": "$-11$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-05",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-nature-roots",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "For which values of $k$ will the equation $x^2-6x+k=0$ have two unequal real roots?",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$\\Delta=b^2-4ac=(-6)^2-4(1)(k)$",
            "For two unequal real roots: $36-4k>0$",
            "$k<9$"
          ],
          "answer": "$k<9$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Determine the value(s) of $p$ for which $2x^2+px+8=0$ has equal roots.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$\\Delta=p^2-4(2)(8)=0$",
            "$p^2=64$",
            "$p=8$ or $p=-8$"
          ],
          "answer": "$p=\\pm 8$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Show that the roots of $x^2+(k+1)x+k=0$ are real and rational for ALL real values of $k$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$\\Delta=(k+1)^2-4(1)(k)$",
            "$=k^2+2k+1-4k$",
            "$=k^2-2k+1=(k-1)^2$",
            "$(k-1)^2\\geq 0$ for all $k$, and it is a perfect square, so the roots are real and rational for all real $k$"
          ],
          "answer": "$\\Delta=(k-1)^2\\geq 0$, a perfect square, so the roots are always real and rational"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-06",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-exp-equation",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $2^{2x}-6\\cdot 2^x+8=0$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "Let $u=2^x$: $u^2-6u+8=0$",
            "$(u-2)(u-4)=0$, so $u=2$ or $u=4$",
            "$2^x=2^1$ gives $x=1$",
            "$2^x=2^2$ gives $x=2$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=1$ or $x=2$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x^{\\frac{2}{3}}=4$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$\\left(x^{\\frac{1}{3}}\\right)^2=4$",
            "$x^{\\frac{1}{3}}=\\pm 2$",
            "$x=(\\pm 2)^3$, so $x=8$ or $x=-8$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=8$ or $x=-8$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-07",
      "difficulty": 3,
      "context": "The roots of the equation $x^2-px+12=0$ differ by exactly $1$.",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-level4",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Determine the possible value(s) of $p$.",
          "marks": 5,
          "solution": [
            "Let the roots be $r$ and $r+1$",
            "Product of roots: $r(r+1)=12$",
            "$r^2+r-12=0$, so $(r+4)(r-3)=0$, giving $r=3$ or $r=-4$",
            "Sum of roots: $p=r+(r+1)=2r+1$",
            "If $r=3$: roots are $3$ and $4$, so $p=7$; if $r=-4$: roots are $-4$ and $-3$, so $p=-7$"
          ],
          "answer": "$p=7$ or $p=-7$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-08",
      "difficulty": 1,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-factor",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x^2+3x-28=0$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "solution": [
            "$(x+7)(x-4)=0$",
            "$x=-7$ or $x=4$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=-7$ or $x=4$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $5x^2=20x$.",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$5x^2-20x=0$ (do NOT divide by $x$ — that loses a solution)",
            "$5x(x-4)=0$",
            "$x=0$ or $x=4$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=0$ or $x=4$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-09",
      "difficulty": 1,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-formula",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$, correct to TWO decimal places: $2x^2-5x-4=0$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$x=\\dfrac{-b\\pm\\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$ with $a=2$, $b=-5$, $c=-4$",
            "$x=\\dfrac{5\\pm\\sqrt{(-5)^2-4(2)(-4)}}{2(2)}=\\dfrac{5\\pm\\sqrt{57}}{4}$",
            "$x=3{,}14$ or $x=-0{,}64$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=3{,}14$ or $x=-0{,}64$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-10",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-inequality",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x^2+2x-15\\geq 0$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$(x+5)(x-3)\\geq 0$",
            "Critical values $x=-5$ and $x=3$",
            "The parabola opens upwards, so it is non-negative on or outside the roots",
            "$x\\leq -5$ or $x\\geq 3$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x\\leq -5$ or $x\\geq 3$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-11",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-quad-inequality",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $(x+2)(x-4)>7$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "The right-hand side is not $0$, so first expand: $x^2-2x-8>7$",
            "$x^2-2x-15>0$",
            "$(x-5)(x+3)>0$",
            "Critical values $x=-3$ and $x=5$; the parabola is positive outside the roots: $x<-3$ or $x>5$"
          ],
          "answer": "$x<-3$ or $x>5$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-12",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-surd-equation",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $\\sqrt{2x+3}=x$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "Square both sides: $2x+3=x^2$",
            "$x^2-2x-3=0$",
            "$(x-3)(x+1)=0$, so $x=3$ or $x=-1$",
            "Check $x=-1$: LHS $=\\sqrt{1}=1$ but RHS $=-1$, so $x=-1$ is not valid; check $x=3$: LHS $=\\sqrt{9}=3=$ RHS",
            "$x=3$ only"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=3$ (the solution $x=-1$ is extraneous)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-13",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-surd-equation",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve for $x$: $x-\\sqrt{x+1}=5$.",
          "marks": 5,
          "solution": [
            "Isolate the surd: $\\sqrt{x+1}=x-5$",
            "Square both sides: $x+1=x^2-10x+25$",
            "$x^2-11x+24=0$",
            "$(x-3)(x-8)=0$, so $x=3$ or $x=8$",
            "Check $x=3$: $3-\\sqrt{4}=3-2=1\\neq 5$, not valid; check $x=8$: $8-\\sqrt{9}=8-3=5$, valid",
            "$x=8$ only"
          ],
          "answer": "$x=8$ (the solution $x=3$ is extraneous)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-14",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-simultaneous",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "Solve simultaneously for $x$ and $y$: $y-x=2$ and $xy=15$.",
          "marks": 6,
          "solution": [
            "From the linear equation: $y=x+2$",
            "Substitute into $xy=15$: $x(x+2)=15$",
            "$x^2+2x-15=0$",
            "$(x+5)(x-3)=0$",
            "$x=-5$ or $x=3$",
            "If $x=-5$ then $y=-3$; if $x=3$ then $y=5$"
          ],
          "answer": "$(x;y)=(-5;-3)$ or $(x;y)=(3;5)$"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-15",
      "difficulty": 2,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-nature-roots",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "For which value(s) of $k$ will the equation $kx^2+4x+1=0$ have non-real roots?",
          "marks": 3,
          "solution": [
            "$\\Delta=b^2-4ac=(4)^2-4(k)(1)=16-4k$",
            "For non-real roots: $16-4k<0$",
            "$k>4$"
          ],
          "answer": "$k>4$"
        },
        {
          "q": "Show that the roots of $x^2-(k+3)x+3k=0$ are rational for ALL real values of $k$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "$\\Delta=\\left[-(k+3)\\right]^2-4(1)(3k)$",
            "$=k^2+6k+9-12k$",
            "$=k^2-6k+9=(k-3)^2$",
            "$(k-3)^2\\geq 0$ and is a perfect square for all real $k$, so the roots are always rational"
          ],
          "answer": "$\\Delta=(k-3)^2$, a perfect square for all real $k$, so the roots are always rational"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "algebra-16",
      "difficulty": 3,
      "context": "",
      "svg": null,
      "archetype": "alg-level4",
      "parts": [
        {
          "q": "WITHOUT using a calculator, determine the value of $\\left(1-\\dfrac{1}{2^2}\\right)\\left(1-\\dfrac{1}{3^2}\\right)\\left(1-\\dfrac{1}{4^2}\\right)\\times\\ldots\\times\\left(1-\\dfrac{1}{20^2}\\right)$. Show ALL your working.",
          "marks": 4,
          "solution": [
            "Each factor: $1-\\dfrac{1}{k^2}=\\dfrac{k^2-1}{k^2}=\\dfrac{(k-1)(k+1)}{k^2}$",
            "The product becomes $\\dfrac{1\\times 3}{2\\times 2}\\times\\dfrac{2\\times 4}{3\\times 3}\\times\\dfrac{3\\times 5}{4\\times 4}\\times\\ldots\\times\\dfrac{19\\times 21}{20\\times 20}$",
            "Writing the factors out, every numerator cancels against neighbouring denominators (telescoping), leaving $\\dfrac{1}{2}\\times\\dfrac{21}{20}$",
            "$=\\dfrac{21}{40}$"
          ],
          "answer": "$\\dfrac{21}{40}$"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
